# UI components and utilities

Thunderstorm provides UI components and utilities that **must** be used instead of raw HTML elements or language primitives. The generic principle lives in the coding rules ("reuse infra, never bypass it"); this rule provides the specific mappings.

---

## Prohibited HTML elements

| Raw element | Use instead | Notes |
|-------------|-------------|-------|
| `<button>` | Infra button component | Define style variants (primary, ghost, small, etc.) as app-level SCSS classes — either in `app.scss` or dedicated style files imported into `app.scss`. Multiple variants are expected; they must be defined once and reused everywhere. |
| `<select>` | `TS_DropDown` | **Recurring violation — this is banned.** Two flavors: one for DB entity selection (editable-item pattern) and one for simple enum/value selection. Customize appearance via app-level SCSS classes. Never reach for `<select>` even for "quick" pickers. |
| `<label>` | `TS_PropRenderer.Horizontal` / `TS_PropRenderer.Vertical` | From `@nu-art/thunder-widgets`. Accepts a `label` prop (string or ReactNode) and renders children as the field content, with proper layout via `LL_H_C`/`LL_V_L` and a consistent `.ts-prop-renderer__label` class for styling. |
| `<span>` | Minimize usage | Spans have no semantic meaning and interact poorly with flexbox/grid layouts. Prefer semantic or framework elements that carry meaning and behave predictably. When text display is genuinely needed, use the appropriate infra component or a semantically correct element. |

